When a goddess of war reincarnates into the body of a young girl, a street orphan discovers that he is destined to protect her. Sean Bean stars. (2023)(110 mins)
Nearly 5,000 years after being bestowed with the almighty powers, Black Adam arrives to unleash justice on the world. (2022)(124 mins)
Torn apart from her sister and children, a woman finds great strength in new friendships. Language/violence/sex/mature themes. (2023)(141 mins)
Ex-Formula 1 racer Enzo Ferrari launches his team into the perilous 1,000-mile Mille Miglia race. Sky Original film from Michael Mann with Adam Driver and Penelope Cruz. (2023)(126 mins)
Ex-Formula 1 racer Enzo Ferrari launches his team into the perilous 1,000-mile Mille Miglia race. Sky Original film from Michael Mann with Adam Driver and Penelope Cruz. (2023)(126 mins) Also in UHD.
Sky Original film following Welsh hairdresser Liz Evans' fight to save her small town's theatre. Poignant British drama based on a true story starring Samantha Morton. (2022)(109 mins)
Out of Order is a new gameshow all about judgements and first impressions. Host Rosie Jones is joined by team captains Katherine Ryan and Judi Love, plus Chris McCausland & Richard Osman. (S1, E01)
Infected: After escaping the QZ, Joel and Tess clash over Ellie's fate while navigating the ruins of Boston. (S1, ep 2 of 9)
Please Hold to my Hand: After abandoning their truck, Joel and Ellie try to escape without drawing a rebel leader's attention. (S1, ep 4 of 9)
New & Exclusive. The Hunt: Mary resorts to drastic measures to help her son impress the king. George attempts to stand out from the crowd. (S1, ep 2 of 7)
New & Exclusive. Not So Much as Love By Awe: As Somerset puts George under pressure, Mary must find a way to persevere or risk losing everything. (S1, ep 3 of 7)
In this modern David v Goliath tale, the Wall Street script is flipped as everyday people get rich off GameStop stock. Comedy. Language/mature themes/flashing images. (2023)(105 mins)
Faced with financial ruin, a Marine veteran takes bank hostages to get his outstanding payments. John Boyega and the late Michael K Williams star. (2022)(100 mins)
Andy and the Black-Crested Macaques. Andy heads to Sulawesi in south-east Asia to search for a troop of black-crested macaques.
Andy and the Darkling Beetle. Andy heads to the Namib desert in Africa to discover how a darkling beetle drinks water.
Andy and the Flying Fox. Andy heads to Australia and embarks on an epic adventure with little red flying foxes.
As Dan and Frank go in search of a suspect, Dan's feelings for Elena threaten to overwhelm him. Morton, meanwhile, uncovers a new piece of evidence. Contains strong language. (S1, ep 3)
In a near-future dystopia, a detective hunts traders who deal in artificial humans on the black market. Sci-fi starring Jonathan Rhys Meyers. (2022)(101 mins)
M Night Shyamalan directs this thriller following a family forced to take a terrifying decision when held captive. Dave Bautista stars. (2023)(100 mins)
Chloroform and a pigeon ruin Vinnie's bid to steal a tiny horse. A Sky Original with Joseph Gilgun and Michelle Keegan. Adult themes. (S1, ep 1)
When vengeful gods arrive on Earth in search of the magic, Shazam and his allies battle for survival. Superhero sequel. (2023)(130 mins)
An astronaut crash lands on an unknown planet and quickly discovers he's actually stranded on Earth... 65 million years ago. Adam Driver stars. (2023)(93 mins)
My Two Dads: Ted and John's plan to exact revenge on the school bully inadvertently puts them in a parental role. Contains adult themes. (S1, ep 3 of 8)
Frasier Loves Roz: To save Roz from a disastrous about-to-be love affair, Frasier declares his undying love. Confused? You will be... (S3 Ep22)
The Focus Group: The radio show comes under scrutiny when a focus group volunteer their opinions from behind a two-way mirror. (S3 Ep23)
You Can Go Home Again: Frasier struggles to come up with a clever catchphrase for the show, while Daphne tries to avoid returning to England to visit her family. (S3 Ep24)
The Two Mrs Cranes: When an old flame visits Daphne, the Crane household is turned upside down. (S4 Ep1)
Love Bites Dog: When Roz takes the trouble to set Frasier up on a blind date with her friend, it's Bulldog who ends up falling in love. (S4 Ep2)
The Impossible Dream: When Frasier is awakened night after night by a recurring dream, he becomes obsessed with discovering its true meaning. (S4 Ep3)
A Crane's Critique: While enjoying a quiet coffee, Frasier and Niles realise that they are sitting next to one of America's most famous authors. (S4 Ep4)
Head Game: When Niles fills in for Frasier at the radio station, he becomes a big hit with a famous basketball player. (S4 Ep5)
Mixed Doubles: Daphne is inconsolable when her boyfriend breaks up with her, and Niles decides it's time to declare his true feelings for her. (S4 Ep6)
A Lilith Thanksgiving: Frasier and Lilith are reunited when they try to convince the headmaster of a popular private school that their son is the perfect candidate. (S4 Ep7)
Our Father Whose Art Ain't Heaven: Martin takes Frasier and Niles to a posh restaurant and then buys Frasier an expensive piece of art that he secretly hates. (S4 Ep8)
Dad Loves Sherry, the Boys Just Whine: Frasier and Niles are surprised by Martin's reaction to being dumped by his girlfriend, Maureen. (S4 Ep9)
Liar! Liar!: Frasier finds himself in a precarious situation when he attempts to sort out the troubled marriage of an old high school acquaintance. (S4 Ep10)
Three Days of the Condo: Frasier stands for Condo Board President because he is unhappy about how the building is run. Niles lends his apartment to Martin and Sherry. (S4 Ep11)
Death and the Dog: On a quiet day at the radio station, Frasier tells a depressed caller about Eddie's recent run-in with the dog therapist. (S4 Ep12)
Four for the Seesaw: When Frasier and Niles invite dates on a romantic weekend vacation, they become confused about the ladies' intentions. (S4 Ep13)
To Kill a Talking Bird: When Niles moves into a prestigious new building that doesn't allow cats or dogs, he buys himself a talking bird that ends up causing more problems. (S4 Ep14)
Roz's Krantz & Gouldenstein Are Dead: Roz serves a community service order at a retirement home, but all the people she looks after pass away. (S4 Ep15)
The Unnatural: Frasier tries to stop Frederick from realising that he's a less-than-perfect father when he fills in on the radio station's baseball team. (S4 Ep16)
Roz's Turn: When a spot opens up at the radio station for a new talk-show host, Roz decides that it's her turn to host her own show. (S4 Ep17)
Ham Radio: Frasier's attempt to produce a live, 1940s-style radio drama for KACL's 50th anniversary proves disastrous when Niles takes matters into his own hands. (S4 Ep18)
Three Dates and a Breakup (Part 1/2): Frasier goes on dates with three very different women, while Martin and Sherry consider splitting up. (S4 Ep19)
Three Dates and a Breakup (Part 2/2): Frasier and Niles celebrate Sherry's departure with glee, but she won't give up on Martin that easily. (S4 Ep20)
Daphne Hates Sherry: Daphne and Sherry just can't get on, so Daphne decides to stay at Niles's apartment. And Niles can't believe his luck. (S4 Ep21)
Are You Being Served?: Frasier attempts to console a distraught Niles after Maris sends him their divorce papers. (S4 Ep22)
Ask Me No Questions: When Niles asks his brother if he and Maris should stay together, Frasier is required to give his answer some careful and considered thought. (S4 Ep23)
Odd Man Out: Frasier makes a spontaneous move when he realises that being single isn't all it's cracked up to be. (S4 Ep24)
Frasier's Imaginary Friend: Frasier starts dating a model but their busy schedules make it difficult for them to meet, leading his family to suspect that she isn't real. (S5 Ep1)
The Gift Horse: As Martin's 65th birthday approaches, Frasier and Niles attempt to outdo each other with their gifts for their father. (S5 Ep2)
Halloween: Niles throws a fancy dress Halloween party to raise money for the Library Association. (S5 Ep3)
The Kid: Frasier tries to help Roz after the revelation about her pregnancy. And he's determined to find out who the father is. (S5 Ep4)
The 1000th Show: Frasier's self-importance over a professional milestone and his persistent sibling rivalry with Niles reach crisis point. (S5 Ep5)
Voyage of the Damned: Frasier agrees to be a celebrity guest on a cruise ship to Alaska, but then Martin decides that the whole family should go on the trip together. (S5 Ep6)
My Fair Frasier: Frasier starts dating beautiful, dynamic lawyer Sam Pierce (Lindsay Frost), but could their conflicting careers end their relationship before it's properly begun? (S5 Ep7)
Desperately Seeking Closure: Frasier becomes determined to find out what went wrong when Sam breaks off their relationship. (S5 Ep8)
Perspectives on Christmas: Martin, Daphne, Niles and Roz each describe the tedious holiday season from their own differing perspectives. (S5 Ep9)
Where Every Bloke Knows Your Name: The Fox and Whistle is Frasier's new local, which is no fun for Daphne, who uses the pub as an escape from life's stresses. (S5 Ep10)
In the final leg of Brad and Barney's epic journey, the pair experience a bitterly cold Norway. The boys head to Lillehammer and try out the Olympic bobsleigh track. S4 Ep6
pvrItems.t: Bradley and Barney Walsh: Breaking Dad

pvrItems.sy: Reichenbach Fails: Holmes and Watson's tech billionaire foe unwittingly gives them a piece of information that could help bring him to justice. (S7, ep 12)
Ain't Nobody's Business If I Do: When Daphne finds an engagement ring in Martin's underwear drawer, Niles hires a detective to investigate Sherry's past. (S5 Ep11)
The Zoo Story: Frasier gets a new agent, who sets him up with an opportunity for some great publicity when a crane at the local zoo is named after him. (S5 Ep12)
The Maris Counselor: Under the care of his and Maris's therapist, Niles is convinced their marriage can be saved - until a surprise rendezvous leaves him devastated. (S5 Ep13)
Ski Lodge: Frasier's plans for a family holiday end in a romantic farce involving the Cranes, Daphne, her friend and a ski instructor. (S5 Ep14)
Room Service: When Lilith pays a surprise visit, powerful old feelings are stirred up in Frasier and some surprising new ones in Niles. (S5 Ep15)
Beware of Greeks: Frasier must confront an old family grudge with Aunt Zora when he runs into his cousin Nikos, who is getting married. (S5 Ep16)
The Perfect Guy: When a handsome doctor joins the radio station as the host of a new show, Frasier can't believe that he is as perfect as he seems and tries to find his flaw. (S5 Ep17)
Bad Dog: There's a hold-up at Café Nervosa, and Bulldog wrongfully takes the credit for saving Roz. But Frasier can't handle Bulldog's five seconds of fame. (S5 Ep18)
Frasier's Gotta Have It: When Frasier begins dating a beautiful woman, he has trouble accepting that the relationship is largely built on physical attraction. (S5 Ep19)
First Date: Niles organises a fake 'first date' for himself with a neighbour so that Daphne won't realise that she is the one he has romantic feelings for. (S5 Ep20)
Roz and the Schnoz: Roz meets the parents of her baby's father and is shocked to discover a family facial characteristic that simply can't be ignored. (S5 Ep21)
The Life of the Party: When Frasier and Niles throw a singles' party, they are both attracted to the same woman, but it's Roz who steals the show. (S5 Ep22)
Party, Party: Frasier tries to hook up with an attractive lady, but there are several obstacles - a broken watch, car troubles and Martin's invitation to Chimps on Ice. (S5 Ep23)
Sweet Dreams: Frasier puts his job on the line by refusing to read out on air an advertisement for the radio station's new sponsor. (S5 Ep24)
Good Grief: Frasier's unemployment situation brings about various emotional responses, including denial, anger and depression. (S6 Ep1)
Frasier's Curse: Frasier worries about going to his high school reunion, because every time a reunion comes up, he has bad luck. (S6 Ep2)
Dial M for Martin: Frasier's unemployed status puts him on edge with everyone and, when he blows up at Martin, Roz suggests that Martin moves in with Niles. (S6 Ep3)
Hot Ticket: Frasier and Niles fail to get tickets to the hottest show in town, and Daphne's behind appears in the Seattle paper. (S6 Ep4)
First, Do No Harm: Frasier undertakes huge projects to make up for being unemployed, while Martin persuades him to date Duke's daughter Marie. (S6 Ep5)
Secret Admirer: Frasier mistakenly thinks that he has a secret admirer while he's dating an attractive new woman. (S6 Ep6)
How to Bury a Millionaire: Niles has to move in with Frasier after his divorce leaves him strapped for cash. (S6 Ep7)
The Seal Who Came to Dinner: While hosting a dinner party for The Gourmet Society at Maris's beach house, Frasier and Niles have to deal with a smelly, washed-up seal carcass. (S6 Ep8)
Roz, a Loan: Unemployed Roz is happy to hear that KACL might be rehiring everyone. (S6 Ep9)
Merry Christmas, Mrs. Moskowitz: A friendly woman comes to Frasier's rescue when he is out Christmas shopping. She recognises him, and he offers to return the favour. (S6 Ep10)
The Good Samaritan: Frasier is arrested after unwittingly giving a ride to a prostitute. To make matters worse, he must explain the public scandal to his 11-year-old son. (S6 Ep11)
Our Parents, Ourselves: Frasier plays Cupid when he arranges a supposedly accidental meeting between Martin and Roz's mother. (S6 Ep12)
The Show Where Woody Shows Up: Frasier receives a surprise visit from Woody (guest star Woody Harrelson), his old friend from the Cheers bar in Boston. (S6 Ep13)
Three Valentines: Niles prepares for a Valentine's date at Frasier's apartment, until a crease in his trousers escalates into a series of calamities. (S6 Ep14)
To Tell the Truth: Niles hires Donny (Saul Rubinek), a legal shark and Roz's ex-boyfriend, to represent him in the divorce case. (S6 Ep15)
Decoys: Niles discovers that Daphne is dating Donny, his divorce attorney, so he hatches a plan to get Donny back together with Roz. (S6 Ep16)
The Last Bow: The battle with Odin Reichenbach rages, and an old love resurfaces in the last ever episode of the much-loved detective drama. (S7, ep 13)
Dinner Party: Frasier and Niles decide to throw a dinner party but can't agree on who they should invite. (S6 Ep17)
Taps at the Montana: Niles wants his apartment back, but he must face up to both the snooty neighbours who think he is a menace and the person who is renting from him. (S6 Ep18)
IQ: Who has the most impressive IQ - Frasier or Niles? The results of their childhood tests are finally revealed, and one is much higher than the other. (S6 Ep19)
Dr Nora: Christine Baranski guest stars as venomous radio therapist Dr Nora, who joins Frasier at KACL. Piper Laurie cameos. (S6 Ep20)
When a Man Loves Two Women: Frasier dates Cassandra, with whom he had a confusing time on Valentine's Day. Then he bumps into Faye and dates her too. (S6 Ep21)
Visions of Daphne: Daphne gets engaged to her boyfriend Donny but then has a psychic vision that suggests he isn't the right man for her. (S6 Ep22)
Shutout in Seattle (Part 1/2): Daphne's engagement to Donny upsets Niles, but Peppy from Café Nervosa provides a pick-me-up. Frasier keeps getting Faye's name wrong. (S6 Ep23)
Shutout in Seattle (Part 2/2): In the concluding part of the sixth season finale, will any of the Crane men sort out their romantic problems? (S6 Ep24)
Momma Mia: Niles and Martin get the shock of their lives when they meet Frasier's new date: she's the spitting image of his mother. (S7 Ep1)
Father of the Bride: Frasier and Martin inadvertently offer to pay for Daphne's wedding. Meanwhile, Frasier's meddling drives Daphne crazy. (S7 Ep2)
Radio Wars: An unwilling Frasier becomes the butt of pranks by the station's shock jock. (S7 Ep3)
Everyone's a Critic: Frasier and Niles are at loggerheads again when Niles gets a new job as the art critic for a prestigious magazine. (S7 Ep4)
The Dog That Rocks the Cradle: Martin returns from his friend's funeral upset by how it was conducted. Frasier assures his father that all will be well when his time comes. (S7 Ep5)
Rivals: Frasier and Niles compete for the attention of the same woman at a party. At least, they think it's the same woman. (S7 Ep6)
A Tsar Is Born: Frasier and Niles are delighted to discover that they may be descended from Russian royalty. (S7 Ep7)
The Late Doctor Crane: Frasier's name becomes confused with another in casualty. The next day, his death is announced on television and he reads his own obituary. (S7 Ep8)
The Apparent Trap: When Lilith drops Frederick off at Frasier's house for Thanksgiving, Frederick asks her to stay for dinner. But strange things start to happen... (S7 Ep9)
Back Talk: Frasier's back goes, and his prescribed medication causes him to lose his faculties and tell Daphne a long-held secret. (S7 Ep10)
The Fight Before Christmas: An apprehensive Daphne believes that Niles is finally going to reveal his true feelings for her. Frasier throws a poorly attended party. (S7 Ep11)
RDWRER: Frasier and Niles are forced to spend their Millennium New Year driving to Sun Valley in Martin's Winnebago. (S7 Ep12)
They're Playing Our Song: Frasier goes all out when he's inspired to write a new theme tune for his radio show. (S7 Ep13)
Big Crane on Campus: Frasier dates his old high school prom queen but discovers that beauty is only skin deep. (S7 Ep14)
Out with Dad: An unlikely chain of events forces Martin to pretend that he is gay on Valentine's Day. (S7 Ep15)
Something About Dr Mary: Frasier's temporary call-screener, 'Dr' Mary (Kim Coles), hijacks his show with her sassy attitude and no-nonsense advice. (S7 Ep16)
Whine Club: Frasier's hopes of being elected corkmaster of the wine club are dashed when Niles's girlfriend Mel convinces him to run against his brother. (S7 Ep17)
Hot Pursuit: Martin helps Donny to stake out a man who's cheating on his wife, while Frasier and Roz nearly have a romantic encounter at a conference. (S7 Ep18)
Morning Becomes Entertainment: Frasier and Bebe fill in for a week on a morning TV chat show. (S7 Ep19)
To Thine Old Self Be True: Frasier tries to plan Donny's bachelor party and winds up handcuffed to a stripper, embarrassing himself in front of Regan. (S7 Ep20)
The Three Faces of Frasier: Frasier becomes obsessed with a caricature of him that hangs on the wall of a Seattle restaurant. (S7 Ep21)
Dark Side of the Moon: Daphne buckles under the strain of planning her wedding, knowing deep down that it's because her true love is not her betrothed. (S7 Ep22)
Something Borrowed, Someone Blue (Part 1/2): Frasier offers romantic advice to Niles and Daphne, hoping that they'll admit their love for one another before her wedding. (S7 Ep23)
And the Dish Ran Away with the Spoon: In a double-length episode, Niles and Daphne discover that there's a price to pay for admitting their true love. (S8 Ep1)
The Bad Son: Frasier begs Martin to take a tour of a senior citizens' home so that he can ask out its attractive manager. (S8 Ep2)
The Great Crane Robbery: Frasier's bootlicking routine backfires when he invites his new boss, a nouveau-riche dot-com millionaire, to his tastefully decorated home. (S8 Ep3)
Taking Liberties: Frasier hires a butler, who spoils everyone in the household and offers Frasier sage advice in his bid to join the snobbish opera board. (S8 Ep4)
Legal Tender Love and Care: Frasier begins to date the attractive attorney who defended him against Donny, who was jilted at the altar by Daphne. (S8 Ep5)
The New Friend: Frasier develops a friendship with Roz's new boyfriend, who then cheats them both. (S8 Ep6)
Mary Christmas: A scheming Frasier works his way into hosting the annual televised Christmas parade but is horrified to learn that his protégée Dr Mary is his co-host. (S8 Ep7)
Frasier's Edge: On the night of the SeaBee broadcasting awards, Frasier has an emotional crisis that makes him re-evaluate his entire life. (S8 Ep8)
Cranes Unplugged: Frasier can't adjust to his 13-year-old son's new attitude, so he forces Freddy to go camping with him and Martin in an attempt at male bonding. (S8 Ep9)
Motor Skills: After relying on the breakdown service one too many times, Frasier and Niles take a car maintenance class. And when Roz gets a puppy, Martin takes over the training. (S8 Ep10)
The Show Must Go Off: Frasier and Niles try to revitalise the career of their boyhood actor idol, only to learn that he stinks. With Sir Derek Jacobi and Patrick Macnee. (S8 Ep11)
Sliding Frasiers: In homage to the romantic film Sliding Doors, two radically different versions of Frasier's love life unfold. (S8 Ep12)
Hungry Heart: In a comedy of mistaken identity, Frasier intervenes to save station manager Kenny's marriage by diverting him from a rendezvous. (S8 Ep13)
Hooping Cranes: Frasier takes his dad and Niles to the basketball but can't believe his eyes when Niles is plucked out of the crowd and given the chance to win a big cash prize. (S8 Ep14)
Docu.Drama: Frasier can't narrate Roz's ambitious space documentary, so she turns to legendary space hero and US senator John Glenn. (S8 Ep15)
It Takes Two to Tangle: Frasier and Niles desperately search for a wealthy patron to lend support to the failing prep school they both attended. (S8 Ep16)
Forgotten But Not Gone: Frasier resigns from his beloved wine club to avoid a conflict of interest when he begins a new radio show about wine. (S8 Ep17)
Daphne Returns: Niles's romantic chances could be scuppered when Daphne's return sparks a squabble that could end it all. (S8 Ep18)
The Wizard and Roz: Frasier seeks advice from his mentor, who seems more interested in Roz, and Daphne tries to convince Niles that she is psychic. (S8 Ep19)
Semi-Decent Proposal: Frasier agrees to escort his former high school prom queen to her surprise birthday party, but his goal is to spend time with her attractive friend. (S8 Ep20)
A Passing Fancy: Frasier tutors Lorna's son Kirby in exchange for a date with Claire, while Roz gets a day off as a reward for taking Kirby to the prom. (S8 Ep21)
A Day in May: Frasier comforts a crestfallen husband whose house has been put up for sale after his wife abandoned him, taking the children with her. (S8 Ep22)
Cranes Go Caribbean: Frasier is horrified when he learns that Martin, Niles and Daphne are going to accompany him on his trip to Belize with Claire. (S8 Ep23)
Don Juan in Hell (Part 1/2): As Frasier returns from a disastrous trip to Belize with his family, he is faced with the ghosts of past loves. (S9 Ep1)
Don Juan in Hell (Part 2/2): Unsure about whether to end his relationship with his current girlfriend, Frasier is plagued by unwanted advice. (S9 Ep2)
The First Temptation of Daphne: Daphne encounters the green-eyed monster when she learns that Niles is counselling an attractive patient who is obsessed with him. (S9 Ep3)
The Return of Martin Crane: While Martin prepares for his first night's work as a security guard, Frasier, Niles and the gang fuss over who will have to walk Eddie. (S9 Ep4)
Love Stinks: Frasier hosts a party for the staff at the radio station, in order to improve his image. Roz dates a binman. (S9 Ep5)
Room Full of Heroes: Frasier's Halloween party takes an unpleasant turn when Niles drinks a few too many beers. (S9 Ep6)
Bla-Z-Boy: An accident leaves a mess on Frasier's carpet and breaks Martin's chair. Niles gives piano lessons to a talented Roz and a not-so-talented Daphne. (S9 Ep7)
The Two Hundredth Episode: Frasier celebrates his 200th radio broadcast and has tapes of every show except one. But it turns out that an obsessive fan has the missing recording. (S9 Ep8)
Sharing Kirby: Frasier and Niles befriend Kirby when they learn that his girlfriend's grandfather is a well-known wine connoisseur. (S9 Ep9)
Junior Agent: Now that Frasier's agent is representing a hot new radio psychiatrist, she passes Frasier off to her assistant. (S9 Ep10)
Bully for Martin: Frasier offers his unsolicited help when Martin's boss starts acting like a bully. Roz talks incessantly about her new love, Roger. (S9 Ep11)
Mother Load (Part 1/2): Just as Niles and Daphne agree to move in together, they are visited by her disruptive, conniving mother and lecherous, leeching brother. (S9 Ep12)
Mother Load (Part 2/2): After Frasier boots Daphne's unpleasant brother out of his home, Daphne frets that she'll be left alone to deal with her horrendous mother. (S9 Ep13)
Juvenilia: Frasier is ambushed when he agrees to appear on a seemingly innocent teen-oriented radio show but is then interrogated by the brainy high-school panel. (S9 Ep14)
The Proposal: A fussy Niles leaves nothing to chance when he plans the perfect evening as the backdrop for asking Daphne to be his wife. (S9 Ep15)
Wheels of Fortune: Lilith's half-brother, Blaine Sternin (Michael Keaton), comes to town seeking Frasier's forgiveness for his past misdeeds. (S9 Ep16)
Three Blind Dates: Frasier's family and friends set him up on dates with various women who they believe are guaranteed to sweep him off his feet. (S9 Ep17)
War of the Words: Frasier's son wins a spelling bee, but there's trouble when the runner-up's parents find out that Frasier was mouthing the letters of the words. (S9 Ep18)
Deathtrap: Frasier and Niles make a return trip to their childhood home and reminisce about when they thought there had been a murder. (S9 Ep19)
The Love You Fake: Frasier and his neighbour Cam attempt to put an end to their feud because of their parents' supposed love affair. (S9 Ep20)
Cheerful Goodbyes: Frasier meets up with some of the old Cheers gang in Boston for Cliff's retirement party. (S9 Ep21)
Frasier Has Spokane: When Frasier's radio programme is syndicated in Spokane, it replaces a local broadcaster's show, enraging his callers. (S9 Ep22)
The Guilt Trippers: A birthday party held in Daphne's honour sets in motion some rather surprising and unexpected events. (S9 Ep23)
Moons Over Seattle: Niles finally convinces Daphne's hard-drinking father in England to return to her harpy-like mother in Seattle. (S9 Ep24)
The Ring Cycle: Niles and Daphne marry on an impulse while on holiday in Reno but are forced to hide their good news when they return to Seattle. (S10 Ep1)
Enemy at the Gate: Frasier and Niles are pitted against the owner of a local garage in a war over principles and two dollars. Daphne leaves the Crane household for the last time. (S10 Ep2)
Proxy Prexy: Frasier's attempts to become condominium president take a new turn when he persuades Martin to run as a 'puppet' candidate. (S10 Ep3)
Kissing Cousin: Roz's 20-year-old cousin (guest star Zooey Deschanel) is quite the party girl. And when she arrives in Seattle, Frasier finds it impossible to keep up with her. (S10 Ep4)
Tales from the Crypt: Frasier plots revenge on Bulldog after he finds himself on the receiving end of an office prank. (S10 Ep5)
Star Mitzvah: Frasier makes a deal with his Trekkie workmate Noel that he'll get him Scott Bakula's autograph if Noel teaches him Hebrew. But all does not go to plan. (S10 Ep6)
Bristle While You Work: Frasier hires a new housekeeper as a replacement for Daphne, but she proves less than reliable. (S10 Ep7)
Rooms with a View: The Cranes pay an unexpected visit to the hospital as Niles prepares to undergo heart bypass surgery. (S10 Ep8)
Don't Go Breaking My Heart: Frasier is driven round the bend by the new lease of life that Niles has acquired following his midlife crisis. (S10 Ep9)
We Two Kings: Christmas is coming and so, it seems, is a Crane family feud. Niles and Daphne want to hold the family get-together, but Frasier decides that he will host it. (S10 Ep10)
Door Jam: Frasier and Niles enjoy the plush comforts of Seattle's premier spa and are happy with their pampering - until they discover there is a 'Gold Level'. (S10 Ep11)
The Harassed: Tension mounts when Frasier is forced to share his studio and airtime with the station's new finance reporter, an arrogant ex-stock market analyst. (S10 Ep12)
Lilith Needs a Favor: Lilith pays an unexpected visit to Seattle and tells Frasier that she would like another child through artificial insemination. (S10 Ep13)
Daphne Does Dinner: Niles plans a very special dinner party to mark the purchase of a new painting he's bought for Daphne. (S10 Ep14)
Trophy Girlfriend: Frasier asks an attractive gym coach to team up with him for a squash tournament, then develops a massive crush on her. (S10 Ep15)
Fraternal Schwinns: Frasier and Niles are volunteered to participate in a bike-a-thon for AIDS research. Unfortunately, neither of them can ride a bike... (S10 Ep16)
Kenny on the Couch: Frasier is jealous when his depressed station manager finds more comfort in Martin's advice than Frasier's psychiatry. Niles and Daphne study yoga. (S10 Ep17)
Roe to Perdition: The Crane brothers find their social influence growing, thanks to a Russian backstreet caviar dealer. (S10 Ep18)
Some Assembly Required: Frasier turns his hand to DIY and interior design when he helps out with a local homebuilding scheme. Unfortunately, his plans are rather too grand. (S10 Ep19)
Farewell, Nervosa: Frasier and Niles search for a new coffee house when they are annoyed by a street singer (Elvis Costello) who starts playing at Café Nervosa. (S10 Ep20)
The Devil and Dr Phil: Frasier is jealous when he finds out about his former agent Bebe's relationship with his old friend Dr Phil (guest starring as himself). (S10 Ep21)
Fathers and Sons: Martin worries that he might not be Frasier and Niles's father when he notices the similarities that they share with his wife's former colleague. (S10 Ep22)
Analyzed Kiss: Frasier shares an unexpected kiss with Julia while trying to steal files from her ex's office. Niles enjoys a trip to the shooting range more than he expected. (S10 Ep23)
A New Position for Roz: Roz prepares to leave the radio station and join a rival company, but not before voicing her concerns about Frasier's new relationship with Julia. (S10 Ep24)
No Sex Please, We're Skittish: Roz isn't happy when the station announces that it's found a replacement for her, but if she stays she'll have to put up with Frasier's new romance. (S11 Ep1)
A Man, a Plan and a Gal - Julia: Daphne and Niles have an important announcement to make, but Frasier's girlfriend steals their thunder. (S11 Ep2)
The Doctor Is Out: The debonair conductor of the Seattle Opera (guest star Patrick Stewart) mistakenly believes that Frasier is gay and starts courting him. (S11 Ep3)
The Babysitter: It's a battle of the Cranes as Frasier and Martin fall for the same girl - the boys' childhood babysitter. (S11 Ep4)
The Placeholder: Frasier feels like a gooseberry on a night out with Niles, Daphne, Martin and Ronee, so Roz convinces him to go on a date with her friend Ann. (S11 Ep5)
I'm Listening: Frasier overhears his dad's girlfriend Ronee making a date with another man, but when Martin hears the news he accuses his son of eavesdropping. (S11 Ep6)
Maris Returns (Part 1/2): Niles's ex-wife Maris needs his help. Can he keep her return secret from a pregnant and emotional Daphne? (S11 Ep7)
Murder Most Maris (Part 2/2): Niles is suspected as an accomplice to murder, and Frasier accidentally recommends that his brother should be executed... (S11 Ep8)
Guns 'N' Neuroses: Lilith and Frasier are set up on blind dates on the same day by a mutual friend. Niles and Daphne are upset when Martin's gun accidentally goes off. (S11 Ep9)
Seabee Jeebies: After Maris is accused of murdering her husband, Niles becomes famous and starts mixing in the highest echelons of Seattle society. (S11 Ep10)
Frasier-Lite: Frasier, Roz and their colleagues compete against another radio station in a charity competition to see who can lose the most weight. (S11 Ep12)
The Ann Who Came to Dinner: Frasier invites Roz's insurance agent friend Ann - with whom he once shared a disastrous date - over for dinner. (S11 Ep13)
Freudian Sleep: Frasier gets the wrong end of the stick when he overhears Martin inviting Eddie on his romantic weekend away with Ronee, and invites himself along. (S11 Ep14)
Caught in the Act: Frasier agrees to get Roz tickets for Alice to see child entertainer Nanny G, who also happens to be his ex-wife. (S11 Ep15)
Boo!: Frasier dresses up as a clown, to help cure a patient of her phobia, but ends up giving Martin a shock that leads him to make a major decision. (S11 Ep16)
Coots and Ladders: Frasier feels guilty after resorting to crime to spice up his life, but his attempts to put things straight have embarrassing consequences. (S11 Ep17)
Match Game: Frasier hires an attractive professional matchmaker (Laura Linney) but ends up on a string of bad dates. Meanwhile, Niles and Daphne plan a natural birth. (S11 Ep18)
Miss Right Now: Frasier is disappointed to find out that his attractive matchmaker Charlotte already has a boyfriend. (S11 Ep19)
And Frasier Makes Three: Frasier goes out to dinner with his attractive matchmaker Charlotte... and her boyfriend Frank. (S11 Ep20)
Detour: Frasier and Charlotte are stranded in the middle of nowhere when Frasier's car suddenly breaks down. (S11 Ep21)
Crock Tales: Frasier considers throwing out an old pot, but it brings back memories, including the time he accidentally glued himself to an obnoxious blind date. (S11 Ep22)
Goodnight Seattle (Part 1/2): With Charlotte (Laura Linney) about to leave for Chicago, Frasier is offered a job in San Francisco. (S11 Ep23)
Goodnight Seattle (Part 2/2): In the last ever episode of the sitcom, Frasier is feeling lonely on his own in the apartment, and San Francisco beckons... (S11 Ep24)
The Good Son: The opening episode of the classic comedy series in which Dr Frasier Crane returns to Seattle, where he has a job as a radio psychiatrist. (S1 Ep1)
Space Quest: Frasier is having a tough time finding some privacy, while Roz is busy debating the virtues of human contact. (S1 Ep2)
Dinner at Eight: Frasier and Niles decide to take Martin out for a tip-top meal but end up at his favourite restaurant - the Timber Mill House of Beef. (S1 Ep3)
I Hate Frasier Crane: When Frasier becomes the target of a hate campaign organised by a local newspaper columnist, Martin and Daphne encourage him to fight back. (S1 Ep4)
Here's Looking at You: When Martin meets a woman while tinkering with his telescope, Frasier encourages the romance, but his father is suddenly hesitant. (S1 Ep5)
The Crucible: Frasier throws a dinner party to show off a painting he's bought, but when he finds out that the artwork is a fake, he worries that he's becoming shallow. (S1 Ep6)
Call Me Irresponsible: Frasier starts dating Catherine, the jilted girlfriend of one of his callers, and advises the poor guy that he shouldn't try too hard to win her back. (S1 Ep7)
Beloved Infidel: Frasier and Martin finally discover something they have in common: they were both cheated on by their wives. (S1 Ep8)
Selling Out: Frasier is in a moral and ethical quandary: should he do a commercial for a Chinese restaurant? Daphne offers her unique advice. (S1 Ep9)
Oops: Frasier carelessly passes on a snippet of juicy gossip that leads to his colleague Bulldog losing his job. (S1 Ep10)
Death Becomes Him: Frasier is forced to come to terms with his own mortality when a seemingly healthy colleague suddenly dies. (S1 Ep11)
Miracle on Third or Fourth Street: When his son Frederick decides to spend Christmas in Switzerland with Lilith, a dispirited Frasier looks set for a miserable festive season. (S1 Ep12)
Guess Who's Coming to Breakfast: Frasier upsets Martin when he reveals personal details about his love life during a radio broadcast. (S1 Ep13)
Can't Buy Me Love: Frasier agrees to be a 'biddable date' at a celebrity charity auction and is thrilled when a beautiful model outbids the rest of the room. (S1 Ep14)
You Can't Tell a Crook by His Cover: Frasier claims that he can always recognise a criminal, until he and Daphne are fooled by a convincing ex-con. (S1 Ep15)
The Show Where Lilith Comes Back: After finding a lost letter of reconciliation from Frasier, Lilith comes to Seattle and tries to rekindle their relationship. (S1 Ep16)
A Midwinter Night's Dream: Niles fights to resist temptation when he and Daphne are trapped in his home during a violent storm. (S1 Ep17)
And the Whimper Is...: Frasier and Roz are nominated for broadcasting awards but are then tempted to bribe the judges with gifts. (S1 Ep18)
Give Him the Chair!: Frasier feels guilty when he loses his father's chair and learns that sentiment is more important than style. (S1 Ep19)
Fortysomething: Confronted with the prospect of ageing, Frasier has a mid-life crisis and considers chasing a younger woman to prove that he still has some youthful vitality. (S1 Ep20)
Travels with Martin: Frasier, Niles, Martin and Daphne go on an outrageous road trip, which almost leads to disaster for Daphne. (S1 Ep21)
Author! Author!: Frasier and Niles decide to write a book together. It doesn't go well. (S1 Ep22)
Frasier Crane's Day Off: Frasier is off work sick with only his paranoia to keep him company, leading him to believe that everybody is after his job. (S1 Ep23)
My Coffee with Niles: After a year in Seattle, Frasier settles down with Niles to discuss what it's been like to be back together again. (S1 Ep24)
Slow Tango in South Seattle: Frasier fumes when a Boston bar buddy, whom he once helped to overcome writer's block, turns a confidential story about him into a bestseller. (S2 Ep1)
The Unkindest Cut of All: Frasier hopes to stop Eddie from putting himself about after he finds himself foster father to a litter of puppies sired by the mutt. (S2 Ep2)
The Matchmaker: Frasier invites the new station manager home for dinner to fix him up with Daphne. But he thinks it's Frasier who's interested in him. (S2 Ep3)
Flour Child: After helping a pregnant taxi driver to give birth, Niles practises being a father by cradling a sack of flour in his arms. (S2 Ep4)
Duke's, We Hardly Knew Ye: Frasier and Niles accompany Martin to the closing of his favourite bar. But they soon realise they have shares in the company forcing its closure. (S2 Ep5)
The Botched Language of Cranes: After publicly denouncing Seattle as a 'soggy' city, Frasier must battle the angry words and 'gifts' of die-hard Seattleites. (S2 Ep6)
The Candidate: There's father-son rivalry when Martin favours right-wing political candidate Holden Thorpe, while Frasier and Niles support his left-wing rival. (S2 Ep7)
Adventures in Paradise (Part 1/2): Frasier and Madeline run away together to a cottage on remote Bora Bora. But then Lilith turns up... (S2 Ep8)
Adventures in Paradise (Part 2/2): Frasier is driven into a jealous rage by Lilith and her new boyfriend but thinks that he has the perfect opportunity for revenge. (S2 Ep9)
Burying a Grudge: Martin discovers that Artie, a former cop and friend-turned-foe, is suffering in a hospital bed, and thinks it might be time for a reconciliation. (S2 Ep10)
Seat of Power: Frasier and Niles realise that the plumbers who are repairing their toilet bullied them when they were all kids. (S2 Ep11)
Roz in the Doghouse: After injuring Roz's foot, Bulldog offers her a job as his producer. She's worried about his advances but accepts after falling out with Frasier. (S2 Ep12)
Retirement Is Murder: When Martin continues his 20-year obsession with solving a murder, Frasier steps in with his own theory: that the killer was a monkey. (S2 Ep13)
Fool Me Once, Shame on You, Fool Me Twice...: Frasier attempts to work his psychoanalysis on a self-confessed lazy criminal, Phil, who has stolen his briefcase and his car. (S2 Ep14)
You Scratch My Book...: Stunning pop psychologist Honey Snow (Shannon Tweed) makes quite an impression on Frasier, against his better judgement. (S2 Ep15)
The Show Where Sam Shows Up: Sam breezes into town and updates Frasier on the lives of the Cheers gang. But it's soon apparent that he's on the run from a nymphomaniac... (S2 Ep16)
Daphne's Room: When Frasier innocently searches for his missing book in Daphne's room, he inadvertently digs himself into a big financial hole. (S2 Ep17)
The Club: Sibling rivalry is rampant in the Crane household as Frasier and Niles compete for election into a prestigious gentlemen's club. (S2 Ep18)
Someone to Watch Over Me: Frasier is nominated for a broadcasting award but has to call in a bodyguard when he is pestered by an unlikely stalker. (S2 Ep19)
Breaking the Ice: When Frasier realises that he's never heard his father say 'I love you' to him, he decides to crash his dad and Niles' fishing trip for a spot of bonding. (S2 Ep20)
An Affair to Forget: Frasier gets a call from a woman who believes her husband, a fencing instructor, is having an affair. It's odd that Maris is now passionate about fencing... (S2 Ep21)
Agents in America, Part III: Frasier learns some important new lessons and tactics in the fine art of contract negotiations from his agent Bebe. (S2 Ep22)
The Innkeepers: When Frasier learns that one of Seattle's most famous restaurants is about to close, he visits to say goodbye and, in a moment of madness, offers to buy it. (S2 Ep23)
Dark Victory: After counselling his family and friends when all he wants is a little peace, Frasier comes to realise that sometimes you have to put others first. (S2 Ep24)
She's the Boss: Frasier has a new station boss - Kate Costas (Mercedes Ruehl) - and they get on like oil and water, especially when she moves his show to 2am. (S3 Ep1)
Shrink Rap: Niles and Frasier decide to enter family therapy in an effort to get on better. Some hope... (S3 Ep2)
Martin Does It His Way: When their least favourite aunt dies, Frasier and Niles are inspired to help Martin make his dream come true: to finish writing a song for Sinatra. (S3 Ep3)
Leapin' Lizards: Station boss Kate doesn't object to the pranks that Bulldog plays on Frasier, despite Dr Crane's obvious discomfort. (S3 Ep4)
Kisses Sweeter Than Wine: On the day when he's hosting a wine-tasting party, Frasier hires a contractor to remove a scratch from his floor, but he takes apart the whole apartment. (S3 Ep5)
Sleeping with the Enemy: Frasier marches into Kate's office demanding a pay rise. So why do they end up playing tonsil hockey instead? (S3 Ep6)
The Adventures of Bad Boy and Dirty Girl: It's the morning after, and Kate and Frasier are worried about the consequences of their fling. (S3 Ep7)
The Last Time I Saw Maris: Niles decides to stand up to Maris after she disappears to New York for two days on a shopping trip. In retaliation, she moves to divorce him. (S3 Ep8)
Frasier Grinch: Frasier is excited that his son Frederick is coming for Christmas, but Martin thinks a proper Christmas should mean more than just educational presents. (S3 Ep9)
It's Hard to Say Goodbye If You Won't Leave: Frasier realises that he has strong feelings for Kate, just as she announces she is moving to Chicago. (S3 Ep10)
The Friend: Frasier realises that he hasn't made any friends since moving to Seattle, so he sets out to meet someone new. (S3 Ep11)
Come Lie with Me: When Joe stays overnight with Daphne, Frasier is shocked and Niles is... well, you can imagine. (S3 Ep12)
Moon Dance: When Niles decides that it's time to start dating again, he takes Daphne to a posh society ball, but has she got the wrong idea about his intentions? (S3 Ep13)
The Show Where Diane Comes Back: When Diane visits Seattle, Frasier is torn between his feelings for her and his resentment from when she ditched him at the altar. (S3 Ep14)
A Word to the Wise Guy: Maris needs Niles's help, and he thinks it's a chance to get back together. But he has to gain a favour from a shady character in order to assist her. (S3 Ep15)
Look Before You Leap: Frasier suggests that everyone celebrates the leap year by trying something daring - but as usual, his plans go awry. (S3 Ep16)
High Crane Drifter: It's a bad day for American café society as a disgruntled Frasier has his favourite table at Café Nervosa taken over by a rude man. (S3 Ep17)
Chess Pains: Frasier buys an expensive chess set and challenges his dad to a game. Martin wins easily, again and again... (S3 Ep18)
Crane vs. Crane: Niles and Frasier take opposing sides in a court battle over the competency of eccentric millionaire Harlow Stafford. (S3 Ep19)
Police Story: Frasier sets his sights on an attractive policewoman who, unbeknown to him, has a crush on his father. (S3 Ep20)
Where There's Smoke There's Fired: Frasier begins a campaign to woo the new radio station owner, Texas multi-millionaire Big Willy, so that his show will be syndicated. (S3 Ep21)
Frasier Loves Roz: To save Roz from a disastrous about-to-be love affair, Frasier declares his undying love. Confused? You will be... (S3 Ep22)
The Focus Group: The radio show comes under scrutiny when a focus group volunteer their opinions from behind a two-way mirror. (S3 Ep23)
You Can Go Home Again: Frasier struggles to come up with a clever catchphrase for the show, while Daphne tries to avoid returning to England to visit her family. (S3 Ep24)
Fostered: A string of jewellery store robberies are linked to a 16-year-old boy trying to survive the foster system. (S4, ep 10)
